eased","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1285–1309":"1285–1309","1374":"1374","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Warwick Castle, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick Castle, Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England":"Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England","Tanworth, Warwickshire, England":"Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Clay Hall, Tanworth, Warwickshire, England":"Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mitton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from any of the places in Lancashire, Yorkshire, and the West Midlands, so named in Old English as ‘farmstead at a river confluence’, from <i>(ge)m̄ȳthe</i> ‘river confluence’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mitten","meanings":["English (Sussex):","variant of   Mitton  . The English surname in this spelling has been established in Ireland (Wexford) since the early 17th century.","topographic name from Middle English <i>midde</i> + <i>tune</i>, for a dweller in the ‘middle of the village’."]},{"name":"Mittan","meanings":["English: variant of   Mitton  ."]},{"name":"Mutton","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Northamptonshire):","nickname from Middle English <i>motoun</i> ‘sheep’ (Old French <i>mouton</i>).","variant of   Mitton  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaretha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succes